Some privates in the Army fighting in Afghanistan are earning less than the National Minimum Wage (NMW), a new report claims.

The Armed Forces Pay Review Body found the long hours worked by troops, whose pay starts at £17,767 a year, means they may earn less than the £6.31 an hour NMW for those over 21 and £5.03 an hour for those over 18.

The report says: ‘It is possible for those on the lowest pay level to be earning below NMW levels if they work over 55 hours per week, for those aged 21 or over, or more than 68 hours per week if they are aged between 18 and 20.

