The news comes as Nato's secretary general called for increased defence spending in a bid to curb Russian military aggression.

Anders Fogh Rasmussen said member states must modernise their armed forces to check Moscow's intervention in the Crimea.

He told the Daily Telegraph: 'Every ally needs to invest the necessary resources in the right capabilities.

'That means modern equipment, intensive training for our forces, and closer cooperation among Nato allies and with our partners.'

